<DOC><DOCNO> AP880812-0246 </DOCNO><FILEID>AP-NR-08-12-88 0203EDT</FILEID><FIRST>r f PM-BusinessHighlights 2Takes   08-12 0513</FIRST><SECOND>PM-Business Highlights, 2 Takes,0542</SECOND><DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   Major U.S. banks have boosted the prime lendingrate back into the double digits for the first time in three years,reflecting the Federal Reserve's drive to push all interest rateshigher to stave off inflation.   Thursday's half-percentage point hike in the prime, to 10percent, pushed the lending rate to its highest level since thespring of 1985.   The increase is likely to pinch the pocketbooks of consumers whoalready have seen borrowing costs rise in recent months.</TEXT><BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE><TEXT>   Commending ``the indomitable spirit'' of drought-strickenfarmers, President Reagan has signed the nation's largest-everdisaster relief bill.   Also on Thursday, the Agriculture Department said new surveyspoint to a drought-damaged corn crop this fall of 4.48 billionbushels, down 37 percent from last year's harvest and the smallestoutput since 1983.   Grain and soybean futures prices closed mostly lower on theChicago Board of Trade.</TEXT><DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   Retail sales climbed 0.5 percent in July, thethird consecutive monthly increase, the government has reported,but economists say rising interest rates threaten to dampen eventhis modest growth rate in the months ahead.   The Commerce Department said Thursday that sales increased $632million last month to a seasonally adjusted $134.0 billion.</TEXT><DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   Home prices and sales during the April-Juneperiod portray a booming economy on the West Coast, some cooling inthe once red-hot Northeast, resurgence in the Midwest and a hint ofa turnaround in the Southwest, a trade group says.   The National Association of Realtors said Thursday that threeCalifornia metropolitan areas posted the highest home appreciationrates in the country.   A 20.1 percent rise in prices from the second quarter of 1987 tothe same period this year made California's Anaheim-Santa Ana areathe costliest housing market in the nation. Median home pricesthere were $204,000.</TEXT><DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   Bally Manufacturing Corp. says it plans to spinoff its hotel-casino group, which accounts for nearly half of itsrevenue, as a separate publicly-held company but will retain up toa 15 percent stake in the business.   Bally stockholders will receive, tax-free, one share of commonstock in the hotel-casino business for each share of BallyManufacturing they own on the effective date of the spin-off, theChicago-based company stated Thursday.   Bally will retain all components of its leisure andmanufacturing businesses, including its chains of fitness centersand video arcades and its gaming and exercise equipment businesses.</TEXT><DATELINE>BOSTON (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   A federal judge has upheld a landmark patentruling in favor of Polaroid Corp., saying another judge in the caseagainst Eastman Kodak Co. was unbiased even though a relative ownedKodak stock.   ``Under the circumstances, I cannot find that it is the law thatEastman Kodak obtain a vacation of this case up to this point,''U.S. District Judge David Mazzone said Thursday.   Kodak had asked Mazzone to throw out a 1985 decision by anotherfederal judge that Kodak had violated several Polaroid patents oninstant film and cameras.</TEXT><NOTE>MORE</NOTE></DOC>